s of the British Empire. It permeated every aspect of the profession of arms and was an essential ingredient for success in both war and peace. Military Education and Empire is the first major scholarly work to address the role of military education in maintaining the empire throughout the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. Bringing together the world’s top scholars on the subject, this book places distinct national narratives – Canadian, Australian, South African, British, and Indian – within a comparative context. The contributors examine military education within the British Empire as a generator of institutional knowledge, as a socializing agent, and as an enhancer of interoperability. This volume is the first to examine military education from a transnational perspective, which allows readers the opportunity to consider the connections between education and empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary educationzCommonwealth countriesxHistoryy19th century. 0aMilitary educationzCommonwealth countriesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh1 aConnor, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCookson-Hills, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoombs, Howard G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelaney, Douglas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelaney, Douglas E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEngen, Robert C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngen, Robert C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErrington, E. Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzpatrick, Meghan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc